sentences: He had a troubled youth, which he addressed on Battery's 2017 song "My Last Breath".
McTernan joined Ken Olden, Matt Squire, Toshi Yano and Zac Eller to form Battery in 1990.
Originally called "Fury", the band released its first record in 1991 on Deadlock Records.
The band broke up in 1999 but reunited briefly in 2012.

In 2017, the band reunited for good, releasing a new compilation, For The Rejected By The Rejected, and embarked on a tour of Europe.
In 1994, McTernan moved to Boston to be near his future wife who studied at Harvard University.
The first recording produced by McTernan was the eponymous 1995 EP by the New York City based post-hardcore band Texas Is the Reason for Revelation Records.

He started his recording studio "Salad Days", when he was 18 years old, naming it after a song by Minor Threat from their 1985 Salad Days EP, in the basement of the house he shared with six roommates.

McTernan operates a studio called Salad Days in Baltimore, named after the Minor Threat song of the same name, and has produced albums for a number of notable artists, including Thrice, Circa Survive, Turnstile, and Hot Water Music.
His brother, Mike McTernan, is the singer for Damnation A.D. and When Tigers Fight.
